Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls called out:

## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

```csharp
// ReportController.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // PITFALL 1: No more WebForms event handlers (btnExport_Click).
    // ASP.NET Core uses action methods routed via HTTP verbs.

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ExportReport()
    {
        // PITFALL 2: Response.Clear(), .Write(), .End() don't exist.
        // Response.End() threw ThreadAbortException internally — that entire
        // pattern is gone. Return an IActionResult instead; the framework
        // handles headers and content lifecycle.

        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        // PITFALL 3: Response.Redirect("/login", true) called Thread.Abort()
        // to stop execution. ASP.NET Core has NO Thread.Abort — it was removed
        // entirely in .NET Core. RedirectResult simply sets a 302 and returns.
        // Control flow is handled by normal "return" statements.

        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
            // No "endResponse" parameter — just return. Execution stops naturally.
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // PITFALL 4: Never catch ThreadAbortException in .NET Core.
        // It doesn't exist as a flow-control mechanism anymore.
        // Thread.Abort() throws PlatformNotSupportedException if called.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls Summary

| Old Pattern | Why It Breaks | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `Thread.Abort()` removed; throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Return `IActionResult` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse=true` relied on `Thread.Abort()` | `return Redirect(url)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — silently hides real bugs if left in | Remove entirely |
| `Response.Write(data)` | No synchronous write on response body | `return Content()` or `File()` |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | Method doesn't exist | `Response.Headers.Append(...)` or use `FileResult` |
| WebForms event handlers | No page lifecycle in MVC/Core | Action methods with `[HttpGet/Post]` |

## If You Need Raw Response Access

```csharp
// Rare cases where you can't use IActionResult:
[HttpGet]
public async Task ExportRaw()
{
    Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
    Response.Headers.Append("Content-Disposition",
        "attachment; filename=report.csv");
    await Response.WriteAsync(GenerateReport());
    // No .End() call — just let the method return.
    // The framework completes the response automatically.
}
```

**The core insight**: ASP.NET Framework used `Thread.Abort()` as flow control (`Response.End`, `Response.Redirect(..., true)`). .NET Core removed `Thread.Abort` entirely. Replace all "abort to stop processing" patterns with normal `return` statements returning `IActionResult`.
